'''Actes Sud''' is a French publishing house based in [[Arles]]. It was founded in 1978 by author [[Hubert Nyssen]].<ref name="lenouvelobslamortdhubert">{{cite news|last1=Leménager|first1=Grégoire|title=La mort d'Hubert Nyssen, fondateur d'Actes Sud|url=http://bibliobs.nouvelobs.com/romans/20080221.BIB0850/la-mort-d-hubert-nyssen-fondateur-d-actes-sud.html|accessdate=October 7, 2016|work=Le Nouvel Observateur|date=November 15, 2011}}</ref><ref name="lemondeactessudrachetepayot">{{cite news|last1=Beuve-Méry|first1=Alain|title=Actes Sud rachète Payot & Rivages|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2013/01/03/actes-sud-rachete-payot-rivages_1812703_3234.html|accessdate=October 7, 2016|work=Le Monde|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name="legoncourtmolga">{{cite news|last1=Molga|first1=Paul|title=Le Goncourt force la croissance d'Actes Sud|url=http://www.lesechos.fr/11/11/2012/lesechos.fr/0202377505976_le-goncourt-force-la-croissance-d-actes-sud.htm|accessdate=October 7, 2016|work=Les Echos|date=November 11, 2012}}</ref> By 2013, the company, then headed by Nyssen's daughter, [[Françoise Nyssen]],<ref name="lenouvelobslamortdhubert"/> had an annual turnover of 60 million euros and 60 staff members.<ref name="lemondeactessudrachetepayot"/>
== History == The ''Actes Sud'' was a publication of the "Atelier de cartographie thématique et statistique" (ACTeS). ACTeS was situated in [[Paradou]], a village in the [[Vallée des Baux]]. Here, founder [[Hubert Nyssen]], his wife Christine Le Bœuf, (which was the granddaughter of [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[banker]] and [[patron]] [[Henry Le Bœuf]]), his sister [[Françoise Nyssen]], Bertrand Py and Jean-Paul Capitani met and founded Actes Sud. In 1983 Actes Sud moved to [[Arles]].
== Authors == A selection of authors Actes Sud published:
{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|
* [[Svetlana Alexievich]] [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] * [[Paul Auster]], [[Prix Médicis |Prix Médicis étranger]] for ''[[Leviathan (Auster novel)|Léviathan]]'' * [[Henry Bauchau]], [[Prix du Livre Inter]], 2008 for ''Le Boulevard périphérique'' * [[Jeanne Benameur]], [[Grand prix RTL-Lire]], 2013 for ''Profanes'' * [[Nina Berberova]] * [[Sophie Calle]]# * [[Magyd Cherfi]], Price of [[Le Parisien Magazine|Parisien Magazine]], 2016 for ''Ma part de Gaulois'' * [[Kamel Daoud]], [[Prix Goncourt for Debut novel]], 2015 for ''[[The Meursault Investigation|Meursault, contre-enquête]]'' * [[Mathias Énard]], [[Prix du Livre Inter]], 2009 for ''Zone (Roman)'' and third Prix Goncourt at Actes Sud 2015 for ''[[Compass (novel)|Boussole]]'' * [[Alice Ferney]] * [[Jérôme Ferrari]], second Prix Goncourt at Actes Sud, 2012 for ''[[The Sermon on the Fall of Rome]]'' * [[Laurent Gaudé]], first Prix Goncourt for a book Actes Sud published, 2004 for ''[[Le Soleil des Scorta]]'' * [[Günter Grass]], Nobel Prize in Literature * [[Nancy Huston]], [[prix du Livre Inter]], 1997 for ''Instruments des ténèbres'', [[prix Femina]], 2006 for ''Lignes de faille'' * [[Imre Kertész]], Nobel Prize in Literature * [[Camilla Läckberg]] * [[Stieg Larsson]] * [[Alberto Manguel]] * [[Cormac McCarthy]] * [[Wajdi Mouawad]] * [[Olivier Py]] * [[Pierre Rabhi]] * [[Jean-Michel Ribes]] * [[Jacky Siméon]] * [[Siri Hustvedt]] * [[Kathryn Stockett]] }}
== Prizes == * 2004: the book ''[[The Scortas' Sun]]'' (''Le Soleil des Scorta'') by [[Laurent Gaudé]], was the first book published by Actes Sud, receiving a [[Prix Goncourt]] (Prix Goncourt/Roman). The book sold 400,000 copies.<ref name=ASD1>{{cite web|url=https://www.caminteresse.fr/culture/le-goncourt-garantit-il-un-succes-en-librairie-115656/|title=Le Goncourt garantit-il un succès en librairie ?|language=fr|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> * 2012: ''Sermon sur la chute de Rome'' by [[Jérôme Ferrari]] was the second book published by Actes Sud honoured by the Prix Goncourt<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livreshebdo.fr/actualites/DetailsActuRub.aspx?id=9531 |title=Le Goncourt pour Jérôme Ferrari |work=Livres hebdo |author= |date=November 7, 2012 |language=French |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>. * 2015: ''[[Compass (novel)|Compass]]'' (''Bussole'') by [[Mathias Énard]], also published by Actes Sud, received the Prix Goncourt<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/03/frances-top-literary-prize-awarded-to-mathias-enard |title=France's top literary prize awarded to Mathias Énard |work=[[The Guardian]] |author=Ken Willsher |date=November 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>. * 2017: ''[[The order of the day]]'' (''L'Ordre du jour'') by [[Éric Vuillard]], published by Actes Sud, got the Prix Goncourt<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/livres/article/2017/11/06/le-prix-goncourt-recompense-eric-vuillard-pour-l-ordre-du-jour_5210830_3260.html|title=Le prix Goncourt récompense Eric Vuillard pour " L'Ordre du jour "|work=Le Monde|language=French}}</ref>. * 2015: [[Svetlana Alexievich]] won the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]].<ref name="lemondeleditriceaqui">{{cite news|last1=Van Renterghem|first1=Marion|title=Françoise Nyssen, l'éditrice à qui tout réussit |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2015/11/04/francoise-nyssen-la-boussole-du-sud_4802927_3246.html|accessdate=October 7, 2016|work=Le Monde|date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>
== Programme == Actes Süd provides a catalogue naming 11,500 titles. It has more than two hundred employees, mostly at the sites in [[Arles]] and [[Paris]], about twenty external advisors and a plethora of translators work in [[France]] and elsewhere.
